SIMPLE: flight
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flight
<hw>Flight</hw> <pr>(fl⟦imac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>fliht</ets>, <ets>flyht</ets>, a flying, fr.
<ets>fle⟦oacute⟧gan</ets> to fly; cf. <ets>flyht</ets> a fleeing, fr.
<ets>fle⟦oacute⟧n</ets> to flee, G. <ets>flucht</ets> a fleeing, Sw.
<ets>flykt</ets>, G. <ets>flug</ets> a flying, Sw. <ets>flygt</ets>, D.
<ets>vlugt</ets> a fleeing or flying, Dan. <ets>flugt</ets>. ⟦root⟧84.
See <er>Flee</er>, <er>Fly</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
flying; a passing through the air by the help of wings; volitation; mode
or style of flying.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like the night owl's lazy <qex>flight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of fleeing; the act of running away, to
escape danger or expected evil; hasty departure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pray ye that your <qex>flight</qex> be not in the winter.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xxiv. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fain by <qex>flight</qex> to save themselves.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Lofty elevation and excursion; a mounting; a
soaring; <as>as, a <ex>flight</ex> of imagination, ambition,
folly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Could he have kept his spirit to that <qex>flight</qex>,⟦br⟧
<qex>He had been happy</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His highest <qex>flights</qex> were indeed far below those of
Taylor.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A number of beings or things passing through the air
together; especially, a flock of birds flying in company; the birds that
fly or migrate together; the birds produced in one season; <as>as, a
<ex>flight</ex> of arrows</as>.</def> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Swift <qex>flights</qex> of angels ministrant.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a <qex>flight</qex> of fowl⟦br⟧
Scattered winds and tempestuous gusts.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A series of steps or stairs from one landing to
another.</def> <rj><au>Parker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A kind of arrow for the longbow; also, the sport of
shooting with it. See <er>Shaft</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Challenged Cupid at the <qex>flight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not a <qex>flight</qex> drawn home⟦br⟧
E'er made that haste that they have.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The husk or glume of oats.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>a trip made by or in a flying vehicle, as an
airplane, spacecraft, or aeronautical balloon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A scheduled flight{8} on a commercial airline;
<as>as, the next flight leaves at 8 o'clock</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flight feathers</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
wing feathers of a bird, including the quills, coverts, and bastard
wing. See <er>Bird</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To put to
flight</b></col>, <col><b>To turn to flight</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to
compel to run away; to force to flee; to rout.</cd> -- <col><b>to take a
flight{9}</b></col>, <cd>to make a trip in an airplane, especially a
scheduled flight{9}.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Pair; set. See <er>Pair</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flighted</ent>⟦br⟧
